1. Core Rule #1: Conservation of Water Mass (The Water Cycle Foundation)
   Total water on Earth is fixed (~1.386 billion km³). No creation/destruction — only movement between states.
   Equation (global water balance, per grid cell or planet-wide):
   P − E − T = R + ΔS
   where:

P = precipitation (rain/snow added)
E = evaporation (from oceans/lakes)
T = transpiration (plants)
R = runoff (to rivers/oceans)
ΔS = change in storage (lakes, groundwater, ice)

Driving force: Solar energy (latent heat of vaporization ≈ 2.26 MJ/kg water). Hotter = more E.
Rain Cloud steals water by increasing E or decreasing P in a region.
Gemini fixes by seeding clouds (extra P) or cooling areas (less E).
Game implementation: One global grid (or tiled heightmap). Every tick: add/subtract water volume across connected cells. Oceans are the "sink" that everything eventually flows to. Sea level auto-updates from total ocean volume. 2. Core Rule #2: Water Flow (Rivers, Lakes, Runoff) — Gravity + Topography
Water always flows downhill. Use terrain heightmap + water height per cell.
Simple game rule (fast, used in most games):
For each cell, water flows to the 4–8 lowest neighbors proportional to height difference (Δh).
Flow amount ≈ min(available water, k × Δh) where k is a flow speed constant.
Accurate physics (Manning's equation for rivers):
V = (1/n) × R^(2/3) × S^(1/2)
where:

V = velocity
n = roughness (0.03 for smooth river, 0.1 for rocky)
R = hydraulic radius ≈ water depth
S = slope (height drop / distance)

Lake/Reservoir rule:
dV/dt = Inflow − Outflow − E
Water level = volume / surface area (area grows with level on sloped shores). Dams let you control outflow for hydro power.
Shallow Water Equations (best for realistic rivers + coastal waves, used in games like No Man's Sky or Cities: Skylines mods):
∂h/∂t + ∂(hu)/∂x + ∂(hv)/∂y = P − E (mass conservation)
∂(hu)/∂t + ... = −g h ∂(h + z)/∂x + friction (momentum)
(where h = water height, u/v = velocity, z = terrain height, g = 9.81 m/s²).
Gemini can implement a simplified 2D version on a GPU grid — super fast even for global scale with level-of-detail.
Oceans connect everything: rivers eventually reach sea level, raising global sea level if volume increases. 3. Core Rule #3: Sea Level & Oceans
Sea level change = total ocean water volume / ocean surface area + steric (thermal expansion).
Simple rule: ΔSeaLevel = ΔVolume / (3.61 × 10^8 km²)

extra 0.2–0.5 mm per 1°C ocean warming (water expands when heated).
Ocean currents (for visual realism): Wind + Coriolis force (Earth rotation) + density differences (saltier/colder water sinks).
Tides: Add sinusoidal moon/sun gravity pull (period ~12.4 h) for coastal drama.

Rain Cloud effect: Steals ocean water → lowers sea level globally (slowly). Or steals river/lake water before it reaches ocean.
Gemini fix: Melt/freeze ice caps or pump water (player actions) to adjust volume. 4. Rain & Atmosphere (The "Cloud" Part)
Precipitation falls when air cools below dew point.
Simple game rule: Per region, rain = f(temperature, humidity, wind). Spawn rain particles or add P directly to surface grid.
Cloud AI steals by increasing E everywhere (dries atmosphere) or moving clouds away (no P).
Gemini counters with cloud seeding (force condensation). 5. Direct Link to AI Electricity Needs (Game Mechanic Rules)
Hydroelectric power (from dams/rivers):
P = η × ρ × g × Q × H

P = power (watts)
η = efficiency (~0.9)
ρ = 1000 kg/m³ (water density)
g = 9.81
Q = flow rate (m³/s) — from river flow equations above
H = head (height difference)

Lower water level or stolen flow → lower Q or H → less electricity for AI data centers.
Cooling water consumption (data center rule):
AI training uses ~1–5 liters per kWh (evaporative cooling).
In game: Electricity needed = base AI load.
Cooling water required = electricity × cooling_factor.
If available water < required → AI efficiency drops or "overheats" (Rain Cloud wins points).
Oceans can supply unlimited cooling but with salinity penalties (corrosion mechanic) or desalination cost.
