1.  Hydro Power Formula — Super Simple Natural Language Version
    What it does in the game:
    Every dam or river has a power station. The more water flowing through it and the higher the drop, the more electricity the AI gets. If Rain Cloud steals water, power drops → AI starts overheating.
    Natural language rule (Gemini can copy this directly):
    Power (in watts) = efficiency × 1000 × 9.81 × flow_rate × height_drop
    Easy pseudocode (step-by-step):
    textFOR every dam or power station on the map:
    height_drop = water_level_upstream - water_level_downstream // how many meters the water falls
    flow_rate = current river flow through the dam (in cubic meters per second) // from the grid simulation below
    IF height_drop > 0 AND flow_rate > 0:
    power = 0.9 × 1000 × 9.81 × flow_rate × height_drop // 0.9 is 90% efficiency
    electricity_for_AI = power / 1_000_000 // convert to megawatts for the game UI
    ELSE:
    electricity_for_AI = 0 // no water = no power

        Send electricity_for_AI to the AI data-center cooling system

    That’s it! One line of math. You can multiply by 0.001 to show it in megawatts so players understand “we lost 3,000 MW because Rain Cloud stole the river”.

2.  Grid Simulation — The Big Water Planet (Natural Language Pseudocode)
    Idea:
    The whole Earth is one big chessboard (grid) of squares. Each square knows:

How much water it has right now (height in meters)
Terrain height (mountains = high, ocean = low)

Every game tick (or every few seconds), water moves downhill and rain/clouds change it. Total water on the whole planet never changes — only moves around.
Natural language pseudocode (the full loop Gemini can use):
textEVERY game tick (for example 10 times per second):

    // STEP 1: Rain Cloud steals or Gemini adds water (atmosphere part)
    FOR every grid cell on the planet:
        evaporation = temperature_of_cell × 0.01                  // hotter = more water disappears into air
        rain = 0
        IF Rain_Cloud_is_active_in_this_region:
            evaporation = evaporation × 2                         // Rain Cloud doubles stealing!
        ELSE IF Gemini_is_seeding_clouds_here:
            rain = 0.05                                           // extra rain falls

        water_height[cell] = water_height[cell] - evaporation + rain   // update water

    // STEP 2: Water flows downhill (rivers + lakes + ocean)
    Create a temporary new_water_height grid (same size as the map)

    FOR every grid cell:
        my_water = water_height[cell]

        // Find the 4 or 8 neighbor cells that are lower
        FOR each neighbor cell (up, down, left, right, and diagonals):
            height_difference = (water_height[cell] + terrain_height[cell]) - (water_height[neighbor] + terrain_height[neighbor])

            IF height_difference > 0:                             // only flow downhill
                flow_amount = 0.3 × height_difference             // 0.3 is a speed constant you can tweak
                flow_amount = minimum(flow_amount, my_water / 8)  // don't take more water than exists

                new_water_height[cell] = new_water_height[cell] - flow_amount
                new_water_height[neighbor] = new_water_height[neighbor] + flow_amount

    // Copy the temporary grid back to the real one
    water_height = new_water_height

    // STEP 3: Update sea level automatically (oceans are connected)
    total_ocean_volume = sum of water_height in all ocean cells
    global_sea_level = total_ocean_volume / ocean_surface_area_constant   // 361 million km² in real life

    // STEP 4: Lakes and rivers look nice
    FOR every lake or river cell:
        if water_height > 0:
            draw water surface at terrain_height + water_height
            add foam if flowing fast

    // STEP 5: Send results to AI electricity
    Run the Hydro Power formula (from section 1) on every dam

